{"id": "226818", "revid": "38791128", "url": "https://wowpedia.fandom.com/wiki?curid=226818", "title": "Silithid reaver", "text": "Silithid reavers, also called battle tanks, are the main attack troops of the &lt;a href=\"silithid\"&gt;silithid&lt;/a&gt;. They are very aggressive. Reavers are morphologically similar to the &lt;a href=\"silithid%20wasp\"&gt;silithid wasp&lt;/a&gt;, except with underdeveloped vestigial wings. The &lt;a href=\"Qiraji%20battle%20tank%20mounts\"&gt;Qiraji battle tank mounts&lt;/a&gt; are &lt;a href=\"mount\"&gt;mount&lt;/a&gt; versions of these. There is also the &lt;a href=\"Silithid%20Mini-Tank\"&gt;Silithid Mini-Tank&lt;/a&gt; pet.\nIn the RPG.\nSilithid reavers are the &lt;a href=\"hives\"&gt;hives&lt;/a&gt;' primary defenders. They dwell mostly underground or near tunnel entrances, using their darkvision and scent to ferret out intruders. Reavers are defensive by nature and spend most of their lives guarding a particular area or section of tunnel. They do not advance beyond their patrol area to attack, and might seem non-threatening until one gets too close.An average reaver is 8 feet long and 5 feet tall, weighing 350 pounds."}
{"id": "26082", "revid": "39299307", "url": "https://wowpedia.fandom.com/wiki?curid=26082", "title": "Silithid scarab", "text": "Silithid scarabs are part of a caste of the &lt;a href=\"silithid\"&gt;silithid&lt;/a&gt;. Often found in and outside the hives. Many of these silithid are not aggressive unless they or another nearby silithid is attacked."}
{"id": "347678", "revid": "40326557", "url": "https://wowpedia.fandom.com/wiki?curid=347678", "title": "Silithid swarmer", "text": "Silithid swarmers are a caste of &lt;a href=\"silithid\"&gt;silithid&lt;/a&gt; that train the young. Swarmers have been seen in several hives usually with a young silithid following them.\nRPG.\nThis scorpionlike creature has a turquoise body with huge claws clacking at the air. Silithid swarmers carry young silithid. Underneath its shell, a swarmer carries a cluster of broodlings, protecting them with its body. When the swarmer locates prey, it releases its broodlings so that they may learn how to fight. Should the need arise, the broodlings can retreat back under the swarmer\u2019s shell for complete protection."}
